Here’s a **tiny Chart.js** snippet that reads the JSON you built and renders two trend lines: one for *Average Time to Hotline* and another for *Hotline Comprehension %*. It’s intentionally lightweight and keeps the ethical benchmark lines visible.

```html
<canvas id="crisisChart" width="600" height="400"></canvas>

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
<script>
fetch('crisisData.json')
  .then(resp => resp.json())
  .then(data => {
    const sprints = data.sprints.map(s => 'Sprint ' + s.id);
    const time = data.sprints.map(s => s.avgTimeToHotlineSec);
    const comprehension = data.sprints.map(s => s.hotlineComprehensionPct);

    new Chart(document.getElementById('crisisChart'), {
      type: 'line',
      data: {
        labels: sprints,
        datasets: [
          {
            label: 'Avg Time to Hotline (sec)',
            data: time,
            borderColor: '#3b8edc',
            fill: false,
          },
          {
            label: 'Hotline Comprehension (%)',
            data: comprehension,
            borderColor: '#4acf7d',
            fill: false,
          }
        ]
      },
      options: {
        scales: {
          y: {
            beginAtZero: true,
            title: { display: true, text: 'Seconds / Percent' },
            grid: { color: '#ddd' }
          }
        },
        plugins: {
          annotation: {
            // optional plugin to draw ethical benchmarks
            annotations: {
              timeThreshold: {
                type: 'line',
                yMin: data.meta.benchmarks.timeToHotline,
                yMax: data.meta.benchmarks.timeToHotline,
                borderColor: 'red',
                borderWidth: 1,
                label: {
                  content: '2 min target',
                  enabled: true,
                  position: 'end'
                }
              }
            }
          },
          legend: { position: 'bottom' },
          title: {
            display: true,
            text: 'Crisis‑Flow Metrics – Toward Human Help'
          }
        }
      }
    });
  });
</script>
```

**What it shows**
- Designers can instantly see if *time‑to‑hotline* creeps above the red benchmark (120 s).  
- Each data point represents a sprint’s ability to guide users to *real human crisis responders*, keeping the “not‑replacement” clarity measurable.  

This visualization reinforces the one central KPI: how quickly and clearly the interface directs users to live professional help—not how long they stay chatting in‑app.

Yes — a simple bar‑style widget can sit right beside the crisis metrics chart so QA can see accessibility health at a glance.  
Here’s a **minimal Chart.js** example that will plot a few core accessibility scores (contrast, font size, motion fps, screen‑reader tests). It uses color thresholds so violations stand out visually.

```html
<canvas id="accessChart" width="600" height="350"></canvas>

<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/chart.js"></script>
<script>
const accessData = {
  labels: ['Contrast Ratio', 'Font Size (px)', 'Motion FPS', 'Screen‑Reader Pass %'],
  datasets: [{
    label: 'Accessibility Compliance Scores',
    data: [4.8, 18, 10, 98], // mock values
    backgroundColor: [
      '#4acf7d', // good
      '#4acf7d',
      '#f0a202', // near limit (12 fps max)
      '#4acf7d'
    ],
  }]
};

new Chart(document.getElementById('accessChart'), {
  type: 'bar',
  data: accessData,
  options: {
    scales: {
      y: {
        beginAtZero: true,
        title: {
          display: true,
          text: 'Compliance Value (closer to green = better)'
        }
      }
    },
    plugins: {
      title: {
        display: true,
        text: 'Accessibility and Ethical Safety Scores'
      },
      legend: { display: false },
      tooltip: {
        callbacks: {
          label: ctx => `${ctx.dataset.label}: ${ctx.parsed.y}`
        }
      }
    }
  }
});
</script>
```

**Use & interpretation**

- **Green bars** = pass WCAG / design benchmarks.  
- **Amber bars** = near threshold; review soon.  
- **Red bars** = fails; create blocker ticket.  
- Optional: pull live data from audit scripts that test contrast and motion in each sprint build.

Displayed alongside your trend chart, this bar widget lets non‑technical reviewers confirm that accessibility and crisis‑flow integrity stay aligned—keeping the product’s mission visible: calm the user just long enough to guide them to *real human crisis professionals*.

